Chapter Two: Atwight...the lonely blade.<P>            The night was quiet save the storm brewing. Dirk sat in the chair, no light on, pistol in hand and armored in his heavy power suit,<BR>            save his head, on which the helmet‘s visor was open.<P>            His skin had returned to it’s normal gray color as the anger subsided. He was actually a fairly handsome man. He was built like a sword<BR>            blade, long and thin, deceptively slight. He was actually very strong when he needed to be. His dark hair and cool black-and-blue<BR>            eyes had given him his title. Black Elf, they called him. Black in body, maybe, but not in heart. Darkness was his weapon, and so was<BR>            light. But it didn’t control him.<P>            He slouched, actually, drained of most energy. He hadn’t eaten a full, good meal in days-he’d given all of his better food to Trini. A<BR>            smile, melancholy and bleak, rose to his face as he remembered how much his daughter looked like her mother.<P>            Memories rose unbidden. He gritted his teeth, but he couldn’t stop them.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Nall ordered another drink. The waitress looked oddly at him. “Aren’t you a little young for the hard stuff?”<P>            “Just get me it. I need it.” Nall sighed and turned to his grandfather. “I can’t believe that I let her get away.”<P>            “Let?” Reyas grinned in half-elven form. “You got yourself stomped.” He gave the waitress a lewd grin, she blushed and looked away.<P>            “And we bet all our cash on that fight...and that....that....” Nall looked furious. “jerk stole it! We‘ll never pay our debts! We‘ll never fly<BR>            that damn...airship again! We gotta find a job..”<P>            “Calm down, Nall. Calm down.” Reyas sighed. “You have to be patient. We‘ll fix the airship soon enough.”<P>            “Easy for you to say! How old are you anyways?”<P>            “I am not old!”<P>            “So several millennia is young?”<P>            “You wouldn’t know! It’s not the age, it’s the attitude-”<P>            “Boys, boys...” A man in a black business suit was standing nearby. “Please behave yourself.” He looked slightly suspiciously at them,<BR>            then leaned forward conspiratorially. “I was listening. You need a job? I have a business proposition for you..”<P>            “We don’t work for free, you know. Show us some encouragement.” Nall said, the drink beginning to get to him.<P>            The man opened his briefcase.<P>            Nall saw nothing but the shine of the pure platinum bullion inside. One hundred percent pure, shining, glittering platinum bars. He<BR>            found he had stopped breathing. Drink forgotten, his eyes fixed on the man’s face as enchanted by the platinum his wits wandered.<P>            “That pique your interest?”<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Dirk and his wife had lived in the temple since Tunare’s death. He had loved her very much, of course. But while he had been content<BR>            to study, read, and learn most of the time, with only infrequent trips, Jesi didn’t have the patience for that. He had let her go out into<BR>            the world on her own. She had left once-and not come back or even communicated for two months. He had only learned what had<BR>            happened from her.<P>            -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Maxim stared at the dead body in front of him. It was a woman, dressed in evening dress and lying prone. It was old, five years old,<BR>            but showed no sign of decay. Indeed, the wood elf could have been asleep.<P>            “I’m sorry....” he whispered. “I’m so sorry, Jesica.”<P>            [I hate you! I hate you!] she shrieked in his head. [I hate you! You hurt me....Let me go!]<P>            “No. I can’t. You’ll die. I can‘t stand to let that happen.”<P>            [You killed me already!]<P>            “I.....” Guilt wracked Maxim. “You’re...special to me. I don’t know why...”<P>            [Some sign of showing love by KILLING ME.]<P>            “Don’t.....! I...”<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            She had encountered Maxim. He had befriended her, loved her-and finally, had an affair with her. She had been torn, but finally left<BR>            him. They had never found out who was Trini’s father-she had been born shortly afterward.<P>            It had been strange to Dirk. His wife had never showed any signs of boredom or lack of devotion. Her affair was almost entirely unlike<BR>            her. But he had gone on with life, and everything seemed bliss. Then his world came crashing down.<P>            It had been five years ago. He remembered it well-too well. The public record of his wife’s death was only partially true-he had<BR>            watched it happen.<P>            They had gone to Palsa for their anniversary. It had been a wonderful trip, everything he could have hoped for. They had rented a<BR>            hotel room, seen shows, eaten at fancy restaurants. He remembered her laughter, her joy-and got nothing but pain from the memory.<P>            They had been walking home after a night of carousing. Walking on the street. He had gotten a feeling of danger, but he had been a<BR>            little drunk and didn’t pay enough attention.<P>            Then Maxim had appeared, eyes bright with envious rage. As they had tried to grab their weapons and fight, he had sent a barbed,<BR>            spiny chain from his flaming cloak straight at him. Jesica had leapt in front of it. It had impacted her in the heart. Her scream blotted<BR>            out all else, her hot blood had fountained out all over him. He could still feel it and it made his skin crawl and turned the taste of all<BR>            good things to ashes in his mouth.<P>            He had screamed so loud it made his throat muscles raw. He remembered catching her, then turning a murderous eye on Maxim and<BR>            advancing with enough rage boiling his blood to obliterate the universe and everyone in it. But the Hell Lord had surprised him. His<BR>            eyes had widened, then he had sent Dirk, spinning, to the pavement with a hard blow, then picked up Jesica’s dying body and<BR>            vanished. Dirk knew her soul belonged to Maxim now, and the thought burned his mind like the flames that had marred his body<BR>            previously. He had never even got a chance to say good-bye to his beloved. Hatred had nearly claimed his sanity.<P>            Trini was all that was left to him, the only anchor of sanity in a void of despair. But an idea had began to take shape recently. A<BR>            hopeful, terrible idea.<P>            Dirk had his wife’s genetic code stored in his armor’s computer and in several backup chips. If he could just free her soul from Maxim,<BR>            he wouldn’t need her body-which couldn‘t live again, as it‘s heart had been shattered. He could hire someone to make hers again, and<BR>            infuse it with her spirit. And then they would be together again. Since he was dreaming, Dirk expanded on it, adding all his desires.<BR>            They could buy a home in a city or out on the countryside somewhere. Trini would never be lonely again; they‘d send her to a school<BR>            and when she came home they would be normal parents and help her with her work (Not like that was needed, Trini had a miniaturized<BR>            computer chip implanted in her brain with a massive database anyways.). He could do everything he had ever wanted to do but<BR>            couldn’t due to lack of resources. He could maybe even find Yakov and Xedri’s descendants, and maybe even the two themselves, if<BR>            they were still alive. Everything would be perfect........he would be happy again....Trini would be happy. They would never have to<BR>            worry about the menace of the Dread King. He would never be lonely again.<P>            Dirk had quickly lost himself in his fantasy. He shook his head. Stop dreaming.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Reyas wasn’t breathing either. He said in tones of utmost respect, “Sir, I think you just hired us. What do you need?”<P>            The man smiled. “That’s more like it. There is...an artifact I need recovered from the Selvatorian wastes.”<P>            “What sort?” Nall asked, face leaned forward and eyes intent. “What shape, size, weight, characteristics? Also, what’s the pay?”<P>            “Twelve million platinum in bullion, or as much as you can get these for. Believe me, you’ll be happy with it. The artifact in question is<BR>            a sword, hidden in a small catacombs system in the wastes.” The man leaned forward conspiratorially again. “This sword isn’t guarded<BR>            much or in any way difficult to get to for someone of your capabilities.”<P>            Nall wasn’t even paying attention. Twelve million platinum in BULLION? They could sell that for twice that much! They wouldn’t have<BR>            to simply fix the airship, they’d upgrade it! The height of luxury...<P>            The man’s nagging voice snapped Nall back to reality. He grinned impishly. “You got it. Arrange transport for us and we’ll get your<BR>            stuff.”<P>            “Oh, I almost forgot.” The man smiled, a predator’s smile. “The sword is dangerous. Watch yourselves.”<P>            Reyas looked huffed. “Sure. A sword, dangerous to us? You insulting us?”<P>            “Considering the boy’s performance in the arena, perhaps I should just go hire Aquamarine. After all.....”<P>            Nall’s blood boiled. “Now you hold on a minute-” He prodded the man in the chest, razor-sharp claws coming within an inch of torso as<BR>            they emerged from their hidden sheaths. “We are just fine, thank you. You tell us about this job, and we’ll damn well do it.”<P>            “So we have a deal?”<P>            “You betcha.” Nall smiled and shook hands with him, not trusting the shifty-looking eyes.<P>            ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            The man pulled out a cell phone as Nall and Reyas left. “Contact. I’ve arranged for them to pick up the item.”<P>            “Good. Proceed and send a team of Ghosts to extract it and them-at gunpoint. The Director would rather not pay up.”<P>            “How about Team Five? They‘re full strength and equipped.”<P>            “Five is already in Faydwer hunting Lunas and the girl. You’ll have to work with Six.”<P>            “Why again? Six? They don’t even have full strength. And no support.”<P>            “They’ll have to do. The Director has reason to believe that this will be more successful.”<P>            “All right. Six will trail them. Five should rendezvous with Six after recovery. All subjects must be collected as soon as possible. I‘ve<BR>            placed a transmitter on the target.”<P>            “What if they manage to evade the team? Or kill them?”<P>            “Evade Ghosts? Come on. Be serious. As for killing them, I wouldn‘t bet on it either. The teams should be able to defeat them without<BR>            much trouble. Remember their genetic sources.”<P>            Satisfied by his success, the agent of En-Gen lay back and sipped his drink. The key to owning someone was angering them, he<BR>            decided. Once that had happened, you could make them do anything. The phones rang again.<P>            “What?”<P>            “Lillith is gone. We suspect breakout.”<P>            “Damn!” The agent cursed wildly. “Wait. She has a transmitter implanted, correct?”<P>            “Correct.”<P>            “Well, track it. Keep her away from the targets at all costs.”<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Dirk was brought out of dreams of the future by the sound of a footstep. He slowly, ever so carefully, withdrew the switchblade knife<BR>            from his belt and flicked it open with a twist of the wrist. It had been an anniversary present long ago. Jesi had always been<BR>            practical, it reminded him of her again, and it hurt to use it.<P>            Again. The sound of booted feet. He slowly brought the knife into throwing position and with a mental command sealed the helmet.<P>            (I’m up and ready. What‘s on the menu?)<P>            Can it, Starlight. I need infrared.<P>            His vision turned greenish. Ahead, masked by shadows, a humanoid, living, male shape glowed bright green. It was carrying a rifle of<BR>            some sort, probably automatic, pointed straight ahead. Seeing no friendly identity codes, and guessing from the man‘s manner-and his<BR>            natural instincts, Dirk threw the knife.<P>            A sudden flash of green signified the heat bursting from the wound as the knife impacted at the man‘s gut. The man cried out-and<BR>            then started to rise again. Incredible. The knife was tungsten, and would go through most armor like paper. But Dirk had had enough.<BR>            He brought the pistol up and caressed the trigger. A hail of death lanced out again and again and again. After four shots, the man<BR>            crumpled without a sound.<P>            (Nice armor.)<P>            I noticed. <P>            He leapt out of his seat and knelt down to the corpse. Checking for other enemies, and seeing no signs of life, he moved closer.<P>            Lights please.<P>            (Activated, oh mighty military genius.)<P>            Can you stuff it?<P>            He looked down and saw a familiar insignia. Reading it, he got up, and turned to walk away.<P>            “En-Gen. But they don‘t have troopers this tough....do they? What‘s this? ‘Ghost‘?”<P>            A bullet whistled by his visor. Another shot out straight at him and bounced off his armor’s shields. As the neural chip on his<BR>            forehead-the only one, so he could wear armor beneath as well- transmitted mental commands, the nozzle on his armor’s right<BR>            forearm erupted in black energy as a black diamond once part of his original sword received a beam of energy and whirled around. Dirk<BR>            pivoted, letting the prism blade sweep through the shadows. The supposedly dead man cried out again and fell to the ground, a<BR>            bisected husk.<P>            Dirk began to run. Fear for his daughter filled him and he sprinted for Trini’s room.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            So do you trust this guy?<P>            [Of course not. Anyone offering that much can‘t be on the up and up.]<P>            Wow, Grandpa. Your wits haven’t slipped after all. Amazing.<P>            [Remember what I told you about respect?]<P>            Respect is earned. And not by womanizing alone.<P>            [No way! You don’t know what you’re talking about, kid!]<P>            Nall stared out the window at the frozen wastes of Selvatoria. The country ruled the upper north of the continent, and was rich in<BR>            minerals but not in food and water . The rapid euphoria of seeing so much money in one place was beginning to fade. He didn’t trust<BR>            the crew, so he spoke telepathically.<P>            Reyas punched Nall. “Ow!” <P>            [So what are you planning to do with the sword?]<P>            Sell it, of course. If he’s willing to pay twelve million in platinum bullion, then there are others who will pay more. We’ll be rich!<BR>            Wealthy for the rest of our lives!<P>            [Isn’t that a little amoral?]<P>            You were the one who broke our ship. So keep quiet with the moralizing.<P>            [I DID NOT BREAK IT! I was only walking on it and-]<P>            Excuses, excuses. Nall turned and looked at his grandfather, then spoke aloud. “Looks like we’re there.”<P>            The pilot spoke over then intercom. “Ok, boys, this is the general area. Signal us when you’re ready to go back. We‘ll be watching for<BR>            the flares.”<P>            Nall picked up his weapons and left the compartment. He heard his grandfather follow. Seconds later, the massive Dropship lifted into<BR>            the night sky.<P>            ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Dirk ran like a bat out of hell, tearing through ruined corridors and only pausing to catch his breath. <P>            (Stop, hold it!)<P>            WHAT?<P>            (Stealth. Five enemies ahead. MT is really high, and they’re armed and dangerous.)<P>            Thanks.<P>            (You’re too much like your dad for comfort.)<P>            Dirk crept to the area around the doorway. As he raised his armor’s right arm, he aimed, directly for a head that seemed to leap out.<BR>            Five men and women in hard suits were searching the room.<P>            Dirk fired the automatic weapon in his right arm, turning the silence into a violent cacophony of sound. It took one man in the head.<BR>            Screaming, the man hit the ground. The other four turned as one and flame licked the alcove.<P>            Dirk pointed and screamed “Nocturne Beam!” A black beam, aided by the night already in the chamber, tore into a woman, who<BR>            shrieked and grasped her chest. He whirled-and took a bullet to the side. His armor withstood the blow, but barely. He locked eyes<BR>            with the man he had thought down.<P>            No way......these guys are too tough.<P>            Spent cartridges flying from the chamber, Dirk stabbed his arm’s machine gun out at the wounded man. There were blue ripples where<BR>            the bullets impacted, but no damage, indicative of a mana shield amplifying the armor’s shield. <P>            Dirk could play with those too. He activated his. As bullets bounced off his shield, he ignited his prism blade and slashed, killing his<BR>            enemy without a sound. He whirled-and took a black beam in the shoulder. It sent tendrils of pain through his left side.<P>            NO WAY. That’s biologically impossible...isn’t it?<P>            (They don’t seem to think so.)<P>            Dirk sprayed the room with bullets and rushed in, killing two before they could even draw their melee weapons by the most ensured<BR>            way he could-beheading. The wounded woman and a young man drew reinforced adamantine weapons, the ultra-hard, ultra-light<BR>            black metal shining, the man using a sword and supporting his wounded comrade, who was using a pair of katar.. Dirk rushed them<BR>            with blade held high.<P>            Prism blades operated through generating an energy field and focusing it through a prism. They were superior to laser blades because<BR>            the minute fluctuations in the rotating prism caused the blade to constantly shift and be very difficult to guard against. However,<BR>            adamantine lessened the damage by reflecting the light off in random directions. So the boy managed to parry-the girl wasn’t in any<BR>            shape to fight. Dirk snarled and struck again, and again, and again, striking either blade, shield, or armor but doing no critical damage,<BR>            before the boy thought he could risk a counterattack.<P>            The kid’s attack was beautifully well struck-but futile. Dirk smiled behind his visor and countered with a ten-strike-in-quick-succession<BR>            combo without losing a beat. Though armor shards flew, amazingly the boy was still standing.<P>            Dirk’s face twisted into a bitter smile. He raised his right arm. “Night Blade.” A cone of darkness erupted from the floor and drilled into<BR>            his opponents. The already wounded woman screamed and fell to the floor, her shield shorting out and her mind in agony from neural<BR>            feedback. The kid yelled in pain but stood his ground, raising his own arm.<P>            “Plasma Flare.”<P>            Dirk yelled in pain inside his armor as flame blasted at him. His cooling system tried to keep up, and barely managed to do so. He<BR>            regarded his enemy coldly through the visor, breathing low and steady. The boy was panting hard-but shut up abruptly as Dirk rushed<BR>            in and backhanded the boy across the head, knocking him out.<P>            Then another scream. “PA-PA!!!!”<P>            Dirk’s blood turned to ice, his skin jet-black, and he ran for Trini’s room.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Nall looked around cautiously. “Unguarded my a--.” he said, and looked up again<P>            Five men in the uniforms of Selvatorian troops stood guard over a strange-looking ruin in the barren, frozen wastes.<P>            “Five. No trouble.” Reyas answered.<P>            “That’s not the point. If he lied to us, we could be set up.” Nall cautiously aimed his rifle. “Here goes. Mana Wave!”<P>            A wave of azure energy crossed the area between them and tore into a trooper, spinning him around and dropping him to the snow.<BR>            as he rose again, a bullet from Nall’s railgun rifle broke the sound barrier and smashed into the enemy with all the grace and<BR>            gentleness of a sledgehammer. The man dropped to the ground, his helmet a ruin of steel and plastic, and did not rise again.<P>            The remaining four fired as one, the roar of their weapons shattering all semblance of peace. The bullets were fired at Reyas.<P>            “Grandpa!”<P>            Reyas pulled a blade of mana from nowhere and concentrated. Nall heard a series of crackling noises and another Selvatorian fell dead<BR>            as Reyas deflected the bullets with his blade. Nall whistled.<P>            The remaining three did the only thing available to them. They charged, two of them tossing fireballs as they went.<P>            Nall felt his skin and armor burn from the heat, but still managed to keep his aim. A round of shots and his attacker fell dead. Then<BR>            they were within minimum range. Nall leapt to one side and clawed at another one. The claws went through the light steel breastplate<BR>            easily and pierced the man beneath. As internal organs shredded, the man fell dead with a strangled scream.<P>            The last man launched himself into a berserker-like charge, running straight past Nall and swiping at Reyas with the bayonet on his<BR>            rifle. The two traded blows for a bit before Reyas ran his broadsword right through the middle of his assailant. The last man collapsed<BR>            like a doll without strings.<P>            “Nice work Grandpa. Guess you’re good for something besides womanizing after all.”<P>            “Thanks-and I can still kick your butt, young whippersnapper.” Reyas pointed. “After you.”<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Dirk ran into the room where Trini slept. He stopped immediately.<P>            “Don’t move, Lunas.” A group of three, heavily armor-clad ‘Ghosts’ were aiming various nasty weapons at him. One held Trini.<P>            “Daddy! Let me go!” She screamed and kicked at her assailant.<P>            “You heard her. Let her go,” Dirk said, his voice at a dangerously quiet level.<P>            “And if I don’t?” the leader asked with a smirk as he raised his visor. His face was menacing, tough, hard. Brown skin, dark hair. A pair<BR>            of deep-set green eyes.<P>            “You’ll contract a bad case of ‘dead’. That bad enough?”<P>            “You’ll have to back that up, you know. Surrender now and I promise you neither her or you shall be harmed.”<P>            “I know what En-Gen wants me for. No thanks.” Dirk brought his weapons up.<P>            “Your loss. Sergeant, Private, take the kid and go.” The leader spread his arms and brought his armor’s rocket launcher up over his<BR>            shoulder. Dirk aimed his gun at the two, but one of them held up Trini as a human shield and prodded her with his pistol.<P>            “Daddy!” she screamed.<P>            “I can’t....Trini!”<P>            Damnit! Dirk let the weapon down and the two vanished out the doorway to the balcony. He heard the rush of their jump jets.<P>            The next thing he heard was the dreaded tone and screaming of “MISSILE LOCK!” He leapt to the right as the enemy man fired, fire<BR>            jetting out the back of the launcher. The missile lanced to the side and literally blew the roof off. Dirk leapt forward and brought his<BR>            prism blade to life, slashing down.<P>            It impacted another prism blade, a bright orange one which stained the room with argent light. As energy blade struck energy blade,<BR>            his own flashed white and sucked the light from the room. Dirk felt the impact of a dozen bullets as a machine gun licked his armor.<BR>            His screen recorded 5% armor reduction.<P>            Dirk yelled and his body was coated in supernatural fire so hot that it literally sucked in everything, including light particles, black as<BR>            night. He flipped backwards, bringing an armored boot into his assailant’s gut. The man gave no ground, but countered with a brilliant<BR>            streak of argent flame. Dirk ignited his jumpjets and leapt into the sky as his foe did likewise.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Nall placed his boot ever so cautiously on the stone beneath him. Nothing happened, so he relaxed and placed the other one on it.<P>            Immediately alarms started to blare. Nall cursed wildly and Reyas looked around as troops clad in riot armor and carrying bullet shields<BR>            stepped out. There was the ****ing of twenty automatic rifles.<P>            “Drop your weapons and stand down.” The leader spoke through his filtered gas mask. The metallic tone of the voice was odd.<P>            In response Nall simply grinned and struck the ground beneath him. “Catastrophe!” he cried. The ground exploded in fire and many of<BR>            the troops were knocked onto their backs. Nall pulled out his railgun and started firing wildly as return fire blasted over his head. He<BR>            ducked behind a pillar and reloaded. There was no sign of Reyas.<P>            “Grandpa?” he yelled as he swung around and drilled a man with a murderous volley.<P>            “I’m fine!” Reyas pulled out his mana broadsword and struck three quick blows across one man’s torso. The man responded by<BR>            bludgeoning Reyas in the gut, but the dragon wasn’t affected at all. He raised one hand and energy was collected into a sphere in his<BR>            palm. Reyas clenched his fist and screamed “Graviton Beam!”<P>            The energy exploded outward in a lance of death. Reyas pivoted, slashing through support pillars and men, til the beam exhausted<BR>            itself. The crushed remains of Reyas’s opponent collapsed in a heap of blackened, melted metal and melted plastics.<P>            “Nall!” Reyas yelled. ‘They’re machines! They’re not human!”<P>            “Geez, thanks for letting me know.” Nall slammed another clip into his rifle. “I’m running outta bullets here!” He fired again, creasing<BR>            another assailant’s body with thousands of pits and holes. The thing stopped moving after a full round. Not able to take the time to<BR>            reload, Nall dropped the railgun and leapt at his enemies, claws ripping apart steel torsos and bodies with merciless efficiency.<P>            Reyas spun and drove his blade into the floor. Tremors shuddered through the building and the last remnants of the enemy force<BR>            collapsed.<P>            “You could have done that earlier.”<P>            “You were doing all right. Is the young, spry, fit man tired?” Reyas laughed.<P>            “Quit goofing around, grandpa.” Nall pulled a fresh packet of clips from his backpack. “Let’s go.”<P>            The next room was a simple, well-furnished office. There was no surveillance and no traps. On the desk was a gold-plated case.<P>            “This seems to have been a covert Selvatorian base, grandpa. I don’t like this-but as long as there are no witnesses, we’ll get away<BR>            with it. Selvatoria always bugged me anyways.”<P>            “Careful, Nall.”<P>            Nall opened the case. A long, ornate platinum-and-silver long sword lay inside, the blade festooned with lots and lots of small<BR>            gemstones. He picked it up. It seemed to radiate power, and he grinned.<P>            Then a voice spoke right inside his head.<P>            /I don’t recognize you. Who are you?\<P>            “Ahh!”<P>            The door slammed open and he heard a familiar voice.<P>            -------
