“Drop the sword, cutie.” He spun around and looked down the barrel of Aquamarine’s particle cannon.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Dirk spun around in midair and boosted the power to his jumpjets. He drove the blade at his foe with hatred surging in his blood. It<BR>            was parried, then the enemy man snapped his fingers and cried out “Flare.”<P>            Dirk’s armor was suddenly engulfed in bright red flames of which the concussion nearly snuffed his own black flame barrier. He cursed<BR>            and raised his arm. “Lucent Beam.” A bright blade of light crossed the air between them and lanced deep into armor.<P>            Back and forth the duel raged. Dirk had found a worthy opponent, and though the scream of weapons and magic was thick in the air,<BR>            neither could penetrate the other’s defenses. They ripped through the air, and Dirk locked weapons with his adversary and grinned as<BR>            his other hand glowed with black fire.<P>            (Watch your six!)<P>            Then he knew the horror of freefall as...something blasted him in each side and he fell.<P>            It was five hundred feet to the ground. He impacted with a hideous crunch of shattering metal and equipment, felt a shard of torn<BR>            armor dig into his back-and screamed. He stared through his suddenly cracked visor and saw a reddish stain on and near the crack.<BR>            He looked to his side and saw his jumpjets were shot. He looked up to see two enemies about him and cursed in one of the lower<BR>            languages of Hell.<P>            “Nice timing, Rashan.” Dirk’s original foe commented. “It was starting to get a little iffy.”<P>            “Next time, do not depend on our arrival.” said the figure with a two-horned mask, in a male and female voice. Dirk shuddered and<BR>            started to rise.<P>            “I’m not finished yet!” he yelled. The figure laughed and sent a glowing orb of energy at him. Dirk whipped out the modified prism<BR>            blade and parried the ball, sending it back. “I’d rather not keep your little gift!”<P>            The figure caught the orb in a gauntleted hand and smashed it, then laughed. “....Small wonder. You’re too weak to be worth<BR>            anything.” it said in it’s female voice.<P>            Dirk’s eyes and skin turned black as he gave in to his darker side. He raised his arm and screamed “Mar’ak, nealk veelth!” and ran at<BR>            the figure, hatred surging in his veins and all moral values dead. His strike was barely parried, then something hit him and he slammed<BR>            into the rock. He heard metal tear and then started to black out.<P>            “What will we do with him?” he heard weakly.<P>            “Leave him.”<P>            “But my orders were to kill him after extracting a sample-”<P>            “We said leave him. If you want to kill him, go ahead and try.”<P>            The man descended to the earth and got close to Dirk. Through reddened eyes, Dirk saw the hazy form of the man get closer.<P>            “It’s over for you...” and the man aimed.<P>            Then he screamed in pain as Dirk’s left hand went straight through armor as if it were a shadow and clenched in the area of his heart.<BR>            The blood left the man’s face. He writhed and struck weak blows on Dirk’s helmet, which did absolutely no good.<P>            “I...don’t think...so.” Dirk gasped. “Never...underestimate...a demon...even a half-breed.” With no regrets, Dirk clenched his fist and<BR>            felt something-something rather important- tear. Then he let go. “If you hurry....you might live....”<P>            Already screaming and breathing hard, the man rocketed into the sky. Dirk stopped fighting the darkness, and fell unconscious.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Nall backed away. “Oh no, it’s AquaPurine!” he taunted.<P>            “MARINE! AQUAMARINE!!!” she screamed, and fired the particle cannon. It missed Nall narrowly and blasted into a wall. He winced and<BR>            backed up another foot. Recovering her composure, she re-aimed it and repeated her order. “Drop the sword.”<P>            “You think I’m crazy? You ripped me off before, you’re not doing it again.” Nall aimed and fired as she raised her own weapon.<P>            The sound of both warriors opening the gates of Hell to one another was tremendous. Nall saw only a hazy, bluish glow as the particle<BR>            cannon bestowed it’s teasing, crushing caress on his body. He felt pain. Only pain. He dimly heard Aquamarine’s screams, of fury, not<BR>            of pain, then he saw again and she wasn’t in front. <P>            No WAY do you get behind me! He spun like a top and grabbed the sword from the table. With a curse he swung for her shoulder,<BR>            knocking the particle cannon to the ground. As she cursed wildly and struck with her fist, he continued his spin, deflecting most of<BR>            the blow. It still closed his jaw abruptly and made his teeth ache. She fired something at him and he felt himself be propelled by the<BR>            impact. He slammed into a wall with a crunch.<P>            ....Where the hell are you, Grandpa?<P>            -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            When he came to, he may have been screaming. He didn’t know. He couldn’t see out of one eye. Did I lose it? he wondered.<P>            [There’s blood covering it.]<P>            His hand couldn’t reach inside the helmet. He did the best he could and sent a subliminal command to his computer to blow some air<BR>            inside his helm. The blood slowly was washed away by the jets of air-most of it, He stared at the bloody crack in his visor with a<BR>            numbed brain and felt the clotting blood on his cheek.<P>            [You ok? You‘ve cut your cheek to the bone, Dirk. It isn‘t serious but you‘re in shock.]<P>            I think so........He tried to get up and felt the fire of the barely staunched wound on his back. Then again....<P>            [The emergency medical supplies are exhausted. You’re gonna have to make do. Are you still any good at healing?]<P>            “Yeah...“ he whispered and felt the cool blue light infusing his wounds.<P>            [You took one hell of a beating, Dirk. I’ve never seen that happen before.]<P>            “I suppose that guy was really, really good.” he said aloud. The screaming fire of his wounds was only barely cushioned. “Starlight, did<BR>            you hear me? I feel like I’ve been screaming.”<P>            [You were.]<P>            “.......What?”<P>            [You were talking to someone in your dreams. It sounded like.....you were talking to Jesi.]<P>            A chill washed over Dirk, but he got weakly to his feet. “Well this is a fix, eh? No jumpjets, no transport, and no shelter. Any ideas?”<P>            [There has to be some transports left behind. It looked like it was a team of twenty men, and you put down six. A standard light<BR>            transport-the only kind they could have gotten over here because of the no-fly zones- holds four to six people and a bedroom to<BR>            sleep in.]<P>            “I can’t fly one. The last flying course I took was about five years old.” Dirk answered as he picked his way over the broken rocks<BR>            towards the ruined temple. “And what happens if they linked the controls? Anyways, why do you think that they packed their<BR>            troopers comfortably?”<P>            [We’ll make do. Even if they had packed them like sardines, think about it. Ammunition. Armor. Food.. Probably some genetic<BR>            equipment. I’m willing to bet we’ll have a spare. ]<P>            “Aren’t you unstoppable.” He laughed. It was good to have at least one person rooting for him. “You do know these healing spells are<BR>            a temporary thing, right? It’s basically jury-rigging.”<P>            [Yes. You should be ok, though. As long as the transport holds medical supplies, that is.]<P>            The sunlight filled the ruined structure as Dirk walked down the halls, searching for the room and it’s two unconscious occupants.<BR>            Memories, happy ones, mocked his pain. The feeling of light-headedness began to grow as he lost more blood, leaving slightly<BR>            reddened footsteps occasionally. He would pause about every five minutes to reseal the wounds and preserve blood.<P>            [The spot where you left the two was around here.]<P>            “I know.” Dirk pointed his weapon straight ahead, and as he strode forward he saw two tumbled forms.<P>            “Wake up.” he said quietly, and tapped the kid’s helmet.<P>            The sound of the pistol being pulled out and aimed at Dirk’s cracked visor was the rasp of metal on leather. Dirk stared down the<BR>            muzzle of it, then as the kid fired he grinned as the bullet bounced off the shield he had prudently put up first and clattered to the<BR>            floor with a ringing like silvery bells.<P>            Dirk struck the pistol out of his captive’s hands. Captive, because both of them knew who was in charge. The woman stirred-then<BR>            leapt up with weapon out, dropping it down as the kid quietly urged her.<P>            “You’re taking me to your transport, and then where I say. Do as I say and you won’t be killed, and we may actually come to a more<BR>            firm, profitable partnership in the future.”<P>            “And if we refuse?” the young man asked. Dirk grinned like the Grim Reaper.<P>            “I’ll kill you and steal your transport anyways. What’s inconvenient for me is fatal for you. Choose.”<P>            The man’s shoulders slumped in defeat, and he removed his helmet. The woman did likewise and Dirk, as a sign of respect, removed<BR>            his.<P>            The young man was tall and fair of face. He was blond, slightly reddish, haired, and had a firm, honest face that spoke of a sense of<BR>            honor and a thoughtful nature. His slightly pointed ears spoke of elven blood, and he had a thin, wiry build. He looked very<BR>            out-of-place in heavy armor and carrying an adamantine broadsword. He didn’t look terribly strong, but he was very, very fast. His<BR>            blue eyes were piercing, a lot like those of a bird of prey.<P>            The woman, on the other hand, was dusky skinned, like desert sand at sundown, and possessed a smoldering beauty, dark haired and<BR>            fine-boned, the sort that challenged a man as well as tempting him. Her eyes were dark and deep, her face was classically beautiful,<BR>            and her figure was quite nice. Her build was deceptively slight, but from a second’s study Dirk knew hers was a strength that showed<BR>            itself only when needed, much like his own. She looked at him with barely held contempt and hatred, while the boy looked more<BR>            curious and nervous then angry. Her features were that of an erudite/human crossbreed, a rare combination indeed.<P>            “What’s your names?” Dirk asked quietly.<P>            “Privates second class Eris and Scott.” the young man answered, pointing to his comrade first and then himself.<P>            “All right, Eris, Scott. Take me to your transport, then set up it’s route for wherever you were intending to take me.” Dirk smiled<BR>            grimly. “I need to have a few....words with your boss.”<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Nall fired another bolt even as he clenched his fist. “Mana Wave!” The blast of energy left Aquamarine feeling numb and her other<BR>            projectile weapon in shambles. She threw the ruined thing aside and glowed bright white for a second.<P>            “Nanoflare!” She hurled a ball of white-hot flame at Nall, who managed to dodge and counter with a strike from his sword. She gripped<BR>            the blade. “LET GO!” she cried.<P>            “Fat chance!” He pulled back.<P>            “Easy there, boy! We‘ve just met!” Nall distinctly heard the female voice. Combat stopped abruptly.<P>            “Did you say that?” he asked, looking at Aquamarine.<P>            She shook her head.<P>            “Down here.” Nall looked down and saw only the jeweled sword.<P>            “Where?”<P>            “Are you always this thick?” The sword was talking! Aquamarine snickered, but Nall flushed.<P>            “What do you mean?”<P>            “Name’s Atwight. I-”<P>            A sudden flash interrupted the sword’s words, and the next thing he knew Nall was struggling as a man grabbed him from behind and<BR>            held a wet rag smelling of chemicals to his mouth. His vision grew dim, and he only barely heard Aquamarine’s screams of protest as<BR>            she was knocked out, and sank down into a welcome darkness.<P>            --------------------<P><BR>------------------------------------------------------------<BR>                        En-Gen Biological Data File. Code Blue Eyes Only<BR>                        ------------------------------------------------------------<P>                        URGENT MESSAGE<P>                        Datafile:<P>                        Subject: ‘Demon’ Race<BR>                        En-Gen Filer: D. N. Athra<P><BR>                        Sir,<P>                        I have been pouring through old records since you have announced to me the target Dirk Lunas. I believe I have<BR>                        discovered the second side of his racial and genetic strands as a result. This information is based on intuition and<BR>                        research, it is not completed.<P>                        Dirk’s blood is high in MTA of an unknown type. This type has only previously been found in Dragons and other<BR>                        mana-heavy creatures. I have tried to identify this particular strand and met with a great deal of success.<P>                        Apparently, this particular match belongs to a species called ‘Demons’. No doubt based on myth and theology, these<BR>                        creatures are more often then not pure evil and inhabit the mythical lower ‘plane’ of Hell. This is supposedly where evil<BR>                        people come to meet their eternal torture. How this strand exists on Norrath is not known, as no Demon has even been<BR>                        sighted in over five hundred years. According to legend, they ceased coming here after the death of their greatest<BR>                        chieftain, Calchisith. How these beings exists in Norrath is a particularly vexing mystery I have yet to solve.<P>                        Dirk’s particular match belongs to a genetic strand I have chosen to term from old records. Succubae (or in his case, as<BR>                        he is male, Incubae.) It is high in an unknown genetic code that seems highly fluid to susceptible changes, almost as if<BR>                        the creature can consciously alter it’s shape and evolution. A smaller amount of a second strand, (named also from old<BR>                        records, no doubt exaggerated, as the combat ability is beyond belief) Reaper, is that of a creature supposedly a living<BR>                        killing machine, able to attack using all four limbs and with incredible natural talent. This ‘Shadow’ magic he is reputed<BR>                        to wield is a biological ability involving the manipulation of shadow and light to solid coherence. Thus, it is highly rare<BR>                        among normal humans or demihumans, and the feeble results we have gained (the weak utilization of a few weak<BR>                        techniques) in our C521 and A523 strand testing are to be expected.<P>                        However, this strand (which I am codenaming D) seems to present an interesting opportunity. As Dirk’s strands give<BR>                        basic mastery of the D strand, his capture and sample extraction could very well lead to our ability to breed many kinds<BR>                        of Demons. As these creatures are intelligent, they may present some initial difficulty, but I have no doubt we could<BR>                        use them as guards and exterminators. As deadly and vicious combat are embedded in the very genetic code of these<BR>                        creatures, as well as occasional sadism, they would be highly easy to train.<P>                        In conclusion, I warn the Director that this subject will be highly difficult and dangerous to snare. Capture and analysis<BR>                        is paramount. If successful capture is reached, we can utilize it for many uses. I would recommend inserting this strand<BR>                        into our current Teams 5 and 6. Though the process of mutation would be painful and trauma-filled for the subjects,<BR>                        that is of no real concern to the Director. If that experiment is successful, we can move on to more advanced tests.<BR>                        Also I must remind the Director that possession of Lunas as well as his daughter is critical. His daughter’s blood carries<BR>                        little to no D strand more then a normal human’s and as a result is not suitable for extraction.<P>                        End File<BR>                        ------------------------------------------
