<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Chapter Four: Tides Of Darkness<P>            Dirk sat with his head in his hands. His body had recovered quickly, even by demonic standards. He had found it necessary to deceive<BR>            his companions about just how dangerous he was, so he played the invalid a few hours longer then he had to. His young-appearing<BR>            face was harsh and sad.<P>            He wasn’t sure he trusted them, and he was left alone with his melancholia.<P>            Trini.....Jesi.....Tunare......Thelis......Yakov...........<P>            I’ve failed them all. Always when they needed me.....I was never there, or I never did what I should have.........<P>            “NO!” he screamed, slamming his hand down on the railing. “I WILL NOT FAIL AGAIN!!!!” He cursed and screamed and slammed his<BR>            hand on the rail until he was afraid it was going to break. His blood boiled and his fiery aura rose to a black inferno.<P>            “Hey, watch it!” Nall ran over to Dirk and tried to restrain him, then hissed as his hands came away slightly burned.<P>            “To hell with you!”<P>            “You could damage the ship!”<P>            “To hell with your ship too!” Dirk turned his back on the angry young man.<P>            “Dirk.” It was Reyas. “Calm down.”<P>            “Calm down? Calm down? You haven’t ever even seen me mad. Trust me, Reyas, that’s one sight you’ll never-”<P>            “Trust me. You’re mad. What’s your problem? Tell us.”<P>            Dirk sighed and decided to do so. His voice lowered as he began to speak.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR>            Long ago.....<BR>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            “Maxim!”<P>            “What?” Maxim’s face was drawn with anguish.<P>            “....the lady is dead.” The healer pointed to Reva’s lifeless body. “I’m sorry, I did all I could.”<P>            Maxim’s face hardened slowly, and gray took it’s tan color. Then the color returned to his face and he howled, an animal sound of<BR>            frustrated anguish, and stalked away.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Maxim Tidias walked to the iron door and opened it quietly.<P>            “What?” from the guard at the door. Maxim never gave him a chance to listen, as he smashed the man’s head with a single blow. The<BR>            men inside came to their feet.<P>            “What are you doing, Tidias? Are you mad?”<P>            Maxim smiled cruelly and spoke in a hollow, declamatory voice. “You fools are unworthy of my teacher’s legacy. Here you die.”<P>            Cries of outrage erupted and the men drew weapons.<P>            He sent a shadow chain through his first challenger. The man howled as he was struck, and then another, and another, and another<BR>            one, tearing his victim to shreds. Man after man after man came at him. All were destroyed effortlessly.<P>            “Mal’Shak!” Another dead man. Maxim was butchering them, one by one. Not a single one stood a chance. Another one came at him,<BR>            brandishing a sword.<P>            “You usurper!”<P>            Maxim wasted no time on pleasantries or comebacks. He simple obliterated the man with a barrage of chain.<P>            Finally Maxim stood alone. He, last of Raziel’s students. The only one worthy of his post. The only one alive........He placed his hands<BR>            on each individual corpse, draining the soul from the cooling bodies with a vicious and sickening delight. Something deep inside him<BR>            screamed at the euphoria, but he brushed it aside effortlessly.<P>            He walked calmly over to the plain black basalt chair which was the Hell Lord’s throne. He slowly, calmly, and coolly sat down in it.<P>            Instantly a cloak of flames surrounded him, burning, searing. Not his flesh. His very soul. He screamed and tried to get up out of the<BR>            seat, but the flames kept burning, and he screamed again. The price of being a Mal’Shak was endless torment and a desperate need<BR>            for souls.<P>            Dimly through the sea of agony he felt, he thought he heard a mocking laugh.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Maxim rode to the forefront of his army. Such a host could not have been conceived of in a madman’s delirious nightmares. There<BR>            were teeth, claws, blades, spines, scaled flesh and coiled muscle. Armor, weapons, all were ready and shone with a light of bloody<BR>            sun.<P>            “Now we march upon the Plane of Growth! Burn everything! Leave nothing standing!” Maxim was used to the fiery cloak, and he was<BR>            filled with blood lust at the thought of the battle ahead. <P>            Then, with a wave of his hand, he created a portal and rode through it.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            As the army spilled out upon the fields of the plane, it was as if a plague of locusts had come to devour a ripe field. Most of the<BR>            guards at the entry point never had a chance. They were simply swarmed under despite their valiant efforts to resist. A few stood<BR>            longer, warding off the blows of the horrors coming at them from all sides. They began to break ranks, run.<P>            Maxim regarded the battle as a foregone conclusion. There was no way that anyone in the enemy camp could withstand-<P>            He was still thinking that when a portion of his army was eclipsed by a massive field of crackling black and purple lightning. The smell<BR>            of burning flesh was unleashed upon the previously incorrupt plane and the screams of the survivors rang loud. The enemy, inspired<BR>            by this new and unseen ally, rebounded. Their rout became a counterattack, and soon everyone and everything was fighting.<P>            Maxim spurred his unholy steed forward and rode to the front of his troops, leading by example the way he always did. He sent great<BR>            blasts of dark chain forward, the weapons flailing and cutting his enemies apart. The plan had not changed. So it would be a little<BR>            harder. So? There were simply too few defenders versus too many attackers. He had plenty of time, and nobody here was his equal.<BR>            He knew it was not going to kill him. To accept the fact that he might be killed was beyond Maxim Tidias. His life was a story, and it<BR>            would not end on the field of combat. The world had been created simply because some day he would stride it, and it did not end<BR>            with his death. Not here, anyways.<P>            The terrified eyes of his adversaries were irritating to the Hell Lord. There was no time to kill properly. He kept his concentration on<BR>            the fighting as he cut his way through enemy ranks. Captains, champions, all fell. All died.<P>            A whispering wind seemed to blow for a moment, a cold wind that smelled of ice. A man to Maxim’s left shrieked as a swiftly-moving<BR>            shadow rose from the ground and pulled him from his horse and ran him through with a fiery blade of dark matter. Maxim whirled to<BR>            face this new adversary, spurring his horse forward, moving to run his opponent down. The shadow stood it’s ground.<P>            Maxim laughed as his horse moved faster and faster. The man was crazy!<P>            The next second was a blur. As Maxim’s steed rushed upon it, the shadow’s blade sang and the horse tumbled to the ground, stone<BR>            dead. Maxim was jerked out of his saddle and half thrown. Stars exploded before his vision and he realized with a jolt he was<BR>            face-down on the dirt. He picked himself up with a speed born of long practice and sent a barrage of shadowy chains at his<BR>            adversary. The chains were brushed aside like rain from a roof.<P>            Then the shadow launched it’s own attack, rippling forward to rend and tear Maxim’s black armor. Maxim guarded, forming the chains<BR>            into a rough blade, and parrying easily. The shadow laughed, a cool hard voice, and swung again, with grace and relative ease. Maxim<BR>            guarded again and counterattacked with a snap of chain which struck a practically stunning blow to the shadow. It shook it’s head<BR>            and dropped it’s dark aura.<P>            It was a young-looking elf, black-haired, pale skinned, the color of marble, and dark-eyed. His eyes hardened, he yelled, and a dark<BR>            fire blazed out from him. Maxim hissed and flew back, burning, and responded with his own power.<P>            For an instant they stood there, locked in furious mental contest, then they leapt back simultaneously and struck at each other<BR>            again. Armor shards flew like little missiles and cut at both men’s faces and arms. Anger was flowing through the air like a river of<BR>            emotion when an explosion blew the two of them back in opposite directions.<P>            The battle swarmed in between them, driving them apart. Maxim breathed slowly for a moment, the turned back to combat. He<BR>            shouted “Onward!” The army drove the struggling defenders back in a stumbling, disorganized collapse of order. Many of them were<BR>            slaughtered. It was carnage that warmed Maxim’s heart.<P>            ---------------------------------------<P>Dirk opened the door with weariness slowing his motions. His armor was soiled with sweat and blood, and it was notched in several<BR>            places. His face was stained with blood which flowed from a shallow cut on his forehead. <P>            “Things go ill, my lady, but we can still hold.”<P>            Tunare was standing facing the window. She did not turn as she replied. “You really think so?”<P>            “I cannot think anything else.” Dirk remained standing. “Why have you called me?”<P>            “Dirk, we aren’t going to win this.”<P>            “We can still win. You are more then a match for the Faceless.”<P>            “No, Dirk, I’m not.” Tunare turned to face him. “I have called you because I want you to take the army and leave the field<BR>            immediately. My children are dying. Every one which dies drains me more and more. They no longer need me, but I need them. This is<BR>            a lost cause. Go.”<P>            “WHAT?”<P>            “You heard me, Dirk. All of you. Now.”<P>            “Milady, that will leave you defenseless.”<P>            “So?” Tunare’s face was ravaged. The death of her ‘children’ had left dark stains under her eyes and her figure was thinner then Dirk<BR>            remembered it to be. She was like an ancient, withered tree before the storm of the enemy assault.<P>            “You are not dying while I am alive.”<P>            “Your own life is worth more!”<P>            “It is worth nothing.”<P>            “Dirk, I want you to know something. I’m not who you think I am-”<P>            “I knew.”<P>            “YOU KNEW? How?”<P>            “Destiny does not lie, my lady.” Dirk was quiet. “I knew from the moment I opened the book. It told the truth. The words-they didn‘t<BR>            matter. It was the knowledge inside the bindings. That‘s why so many people don‘t get it.” He smirked ever so slightly. “Even further,<BR>            I knew that I had killed Innoruuk the moment I felt my blade slide through his ribs. He is merely a ghost of malice now, one that can<BR>            barely maintain his power, let alone try to expand it. And that way he’ll stay if I have anything to say about it. If one ‘god’ can be<BR>            defeated, why not all of them?”<P>            “And still you followed me? You let me put you through all that?” Tunare was incredulous. “You let me use you as a pawn in our<BR>            struggle? You let me let you be ostracized by everyone? You let me take everything from you?”<P>            “I did.”<P>            “WHY?”<P>            “You are my liege. My honor is yours. I could not have asked for a better lord or lady to serve.”<P>            “Why didn’t you set out on your own?”<P>            Dirk smiled bitterly. “I did with Melkor, and look what happened to me.” He knelt before Tunare. “Your safety is still my duty. Let the<BR>            rest of the army leave with you. I’ll hold the door. One life which matters nothing will be lost.”<P>            Tunare thought very fast. “Dirk, I will never leave this plane alive. I know that.” She looked him in the face, eyes pleading. “You<BR>            matter. I do not. I have played my part. My children have grown up and left the home. You have one yet to perform.” She smiled<BR>            sadly. “The offer is reversed. I’ll hold the door. You leave.”<P>            Dirk was silent until he drew his sword. The light shone upon it as he brought it up into a salute.<P>            Tunare smiled. “There were some who said you shouldn’t have been allowed to be born. I think they’re wrong.” She bowed her head.<BR>            Dirk realized that a supposed ‘immortal’ faced with the inevitability of her own demise is a particularly sad sight. “Listen to me. Don’t<BR>            give up. Period. Some terrible things are going to happen to you, but they can be resolved.”<P>            Dirk smiled bitterly again. “Let fate do it’s worst.” He nodded slowly. “This conversation never happened except for the part where<BR>            you told me to leave.” He turned his back on Tunare and descended the steps, leaving his honor in shreds.<P>            --------------------------<P>Maxim finished praying as the massive form of the Faceless One appeared before him. Men ran, only Maxim stood alone before Him.<P>            “Leave this to me, my reavers.” The Faceless turned and with a powerful blow snapped the door to splinters. “Do not enter.”<P>            Maxim waited calmly. He felt the tremors as the two gods moved to battle. The flashes alone-muted by the walls but still very bright-<BR>            were evidence of their physical battle, but he sensed that there were strikes that were beyond his ability to see-to even imagine. It<BR>            went on for minutes without any sign of stopping, but the strikes shifted more and more to the side of his dread master. He thought<BR>            he could hear screaming, and make out words, but they meant nothing to him.<P>            “You fool, Za’Amor! You dare to interrupt this? In the deaths of one lies the deaths of all of us!”<P>            There was no reply. The next thing he heard was a shocking female scream that echoed in his head like an off-center bell. It went on<BR>            for five full minutes until he thought his head would burst. He was thrown to his knees, and staggered to his feet, and against orders,<BR>            crawled into the room.<P>            He saw very little he could later remember, for all his attention was focused upon the center of the room-and Tunare. The death of a<BR>            thing as powerful as she was is catastrophic. As it was, she was on her knees, bleeding from a dozen wounds. Even as he watched<BR>            her body began to turn bright green in mottled patches, then with a sickening sort of sound reminiscent of wet cloth being dragged<BR>            slowly over concrete the green patches disintegrated slowly into greenish gas smelling of loam. The smell of wet wood filled the room<BR>            as more and more of the patches disappeared, leaving gaping holes without anything inside them. Eventually she was reduced to a<BR>            gaunt, little wire-like figure, and her scream to a thin wail. She pulsed once, and Tunare, Mother of All, exploded into nothingness and<BR>            her cry of agony rose to a shriek which tapered away into an unimaginable silence.<P>            He was immediately knocked back down again from the shockwave. The green-tinged explosion rattled his armor and burned his<BR>            exposed limbs. He couldn’t breathe, the air had been incinerated. As it passed over him he felt he was lucky to be alive. The walls<BR>            were obliterated, and patches of his army who had been right outside the shrine with them. The Faceless One weathered the<BR>            explosion impassively, then with a huge, hollow echoing laugh he began to exult.<P>            In a last shot at Cazic-Thule, the Plane of Growth grew greener and greener as the gas that had once been it’s mistress filled the air<BR>            and drifted whither it would. Some of the army of darkness were engulfed by the gas, and soundlessly were smothered in trees which<BR>            grew up from the earth beneath them and swallowed them up. The plane resisted all efforts to destroy the plants and wildlife inside,<BR>            which bloomed with increasing prosperity. But Cazic was satisfied. His hated enemy had been destroyed utterly, leaving only a<BR>            shadow of herself in the hearts of those who yet worshipped her and in places of her former power.<P>            And in Dirk Lunas’s soul.<P>            --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Scott stared at Eris’s sleeping form, marveling at the humanity he only now realized was a blessing. His spine-ah, what a privilege to<BR>            walk! To move!-was fixed, and he had no idea how. <P>            Sleeping was the best word for it, he decided. He had no idea why Eris lay there unconscious, seeing things that he did not, crying<BR>            out words in a tongue he did not know. He was worried about her.<P>            The techs would get-no. He was never going back to his makers again except to exact his revenge. The memory of what they had<BR>            done to him filled his brain with flames. Anger rose in him, anger that had to be appeased. Scott was not a person who could calmly<BR>            tolerate anger. When he got angry, things-and people-got damaged. It was partially a trace of aggression enhancement.<P>            He ripped the large, flashy En-Gen logo off his suit’s remains, pulled out his pistol, and fired once.<P>            The sight of the ruined logo was somehow appropriate. His anger blunted, he though objectively for a time. They had no home, no<BR>            family, and no friends. They were marooned on a hostile continent with horrors striding it’s soil. And worse of all, he had discovered a<BR>            vile talent in himself he did not want to ever acknowledge.<P>            He began to sit down when he felt a pull on the right side of his head. Obligingly, he turned, and somehow knew to go forward. Scott<BR>            took the pull as an order, and he was accustomed to following orders.<P>            He proceeded to a balcony overlooking a cliff. The pull shifted to down. Again complying, he leapt off the cliff into the ocean. He<BR>            came up again without sputtering, for some reason he felt no need to breathe. The pull kept pulling downward and he dived<BR>            underwater.<P>            Now it was forward. He swam faster then he thought he was capable of swimming, and by the same token, he didn’t get tired. Time<BR>            slipped away. He didn’t pay attention to it.<P>            The pull went downward again. He dived further, coming to the sandy bottom. Sharks and creatures of which he didn’t know the<BR>            names swam in patterns about the area, but he felt no fear. His confident manner calmed them, and they let him be. He wasn’t<BR>            paying attention to them. He was paying attention to the sheathed sword at the bottom of the ocean, glittering with the light of the<BR>            distant sun.<P>            The sword was black as a starless night with no moon. It seemed to radiate darkness and he imagined that through the enshrouding<BR>            water he could hear a low murmur. It’s hilt was studded with a dark red gemstone and a black one at it’s pommel. It had a piece of<BR>            parchment in it’s scabbard, which he couldn’t read unless he grabbed the sword.<P><BR>            That was what he was supposed to do. He grasped the blade in his left hand and kicked to the surface, then swam back. It was no<BR>            easy task to swim up, but he took his time, even encumbered by the blade.<P>            For some reason, he got to the cliff in five minutes. It made no sense. But then again, had any of this insane journey made any<BR>            sense? Starting with their assignment? He smiled halfheartedly as he rose out of the water and rappelled to the top of the cliff. His<BR>            soaked jumpsuit was dripping all over, and his light brown hair had been darkened by the water. His pointed ears were like peaks,<BR>            water flowed down from them as if it was snow melt. He walked-soaking-to the room where he had left Eris.<P>            She was still asleep. He thanked fate for letting her be all right, and still a young woman as opposed to those....things they had<BR>            become for but a short time. Again he was struck by just how beautiful Eris was. He had been grown, not born, and he was<BR>            biologically far younger then his appearance and build made him out to be. Thus, he was experiencing feelings and emotions he had no<BR>            idea existed in people-had never even been taught. Scott had had no mother and father to tell him it was all right and to explain. He<BR>            had no family to make him feel welcome. Only a few of the more friendly techs had explained to him, calmly, and sometimes a little too<BR>            clinically, what they were and what to do about them. How to satisfy them and how to deny them. He didn’t really want to think<BR>            about it, it made his cheeks burn with scarlet.<P>            Shoving aside the feelings, he pulled the sword out from it’s scabbard. The dark edge howled-howled?-as it was drawn, filling the<BR>            room with darkness and fear. The howling became a shriek as he tested it against the edge of his adamantine broadsword-which was<BR>            cloven in two as if it was newly dried wax. He was astounded. Adamantine was the hardest stuff he had ever seen before, and the<BR>            sword looked like it, but it was harder then his own.<P>            Magic, he decided. The techs had also instructed him in the arts of magic. There were legends of objects-swords, daggers, armor,<BR>            staves, and other things-that had been enchanted. This must be one. Even now weapons and armor were enchanted, even pistols<BR>            and ammunition, but the past’s artifacts had supposedly been mightier then the present’s. He was startled-and honored-to find one.<P>            He read the hilt‘s marking. The characters were ones he had never been taught, but they were familiar to him. “Despair” it read.<P>            “To he(she? whatever) who wants to use this, you are a moron But you‘re stuck, the sword‘s attached itself to you, so:<P>            The Despair is a weapon of darkness and should only be used in great need. Beware of it. Though it is not evil of itself, it’s influence<BR>            may corrupt the hearts of those who use it unless their will is strong, for it is infused with destruction. Be careful.<P>            Don’t really have anything else to say. <P>            Yakov Shadeleaf”<P>            The name was a mystery to him, but the words and tone were not. He could swear he had heard them before. Oh well. A sad grin<BR>            spread across his face.<P>            “It’s you and me against the world, Eris,” he said quietly.<P>            “Really?” She was awake? Her eyes were closed, and her face was twisted into an expression of agony.<P>            “Are you all right?”<P>            “I saw horrible things, Scott.. Help me up,” she whined. Her dark, enchanting eyes slid open and she smiled at him. He smiled back.<P>            “Ok.” He grabbed her hand and yanked her up hard.<P>            “Ow. You meanie!” She playfully poked him. “Hold on a moment, I have to find something.” She bent over, facing away from him, and<BR>            he stared discreetly.<P>            “Don’t do that.” She didn’t turn around.<P>            He blushed and averted his eyes. “How did you know?”<P>            “It’s sort of obvious. I know you want me, but still.” She rummaged around in the piles of debris and picked up a D.A.P sized tablet.<BR>            “Ok, we can go,” she said, tucking it into her mutilated uniform’s breast pocket.<P>            “What is that?”<P>            “It’s a key. A special kind of key.” Scott got the impression she didn’t want to say any more.<P>            “How do you propose to get out of here? We‘re surrounded by the undead.”<P>            “Simplicity in itself. Hold me.” He grasped her about the waist in a hug. She smiled at him, but the smile was tinged with sadness.<BR>            Concern grew in him. What had she seen?<P>            A ring of sparkling light erupted from the floor. He gasped and nearly dropped her, but she held firm. <P>            “Where are we going?!”<P>            “I have no idea! Hold on!”<P>            Then the room vanished from his sight.<P>            ------------------------------<P>Dirk finished his story in a low, flat tone. It held no emotion in it. The group had gone silent at Tunare’s death and continued their<BR>            silence as he elaborated on Jesi’s death and Trini‘s kidnapping.<P>            “Now you see why I’m angry.”<P>            There was no reply.<P>            “I’m done. I‘m going to bed.” He spun on his heels and descended into the hold. The group continued their silence until he was out of<BR>            earshot.<P>            “A loose cannon, I say.” That was Annie.<P>            “Definitely,” Nall agreed. “But he’s powerful. We’ll keep an eye on him, and if he starts being too rowdy....”<P>            Reyas interrupted him. “Can’t you see? You can trust Dirk Lunas to do what he wants to do-kill Maxim. Past that, probably. He’s a<BR>            good man. He’d kill for any one of us. Think. He’s met too many people who are dead; death is his ultimate enemy. En-Gen has his<BR>            daughter. He’ll kill them if he gets the chance. He’s as trustworthy as any of us.”<P>            “V...Void.” That was Lilith, her words halting. “He...is........in....in...” she looked irritated. Her voice sounded in Nall’s mind.<P>            He is infused with......if that’s the right way to say it. He.....just take him, ok?<P>            Nall nodded and Lillith swarmed him with hugs. He blushed and Annie muttered obscenities she really shouldn’t know. “And Atwight?”<BR>            he asked aloud.<P>            [Take him.]<P>            Nall nodded and ascended the pilot’s house’s ladder. Nall loved flying as a bird does. He slid into the seat with practiced ease,<BR>            remembering the times when he was a child and Ruby Tayus had steered here, guns blazing and the rudder shrieking with stress. Nall<BR>            had loved his mother, and had only escaped her fate because he had been hidden on board the ship and had taken it out alone after<BR>            it was impounded.<P>            Rumor had it that Ruby had been tortured to death. Nall didn’t want to know, Sometimes he dreamed about it. It wasn’t pleasant. But<BR>            the dreams came less and less as time went by. He was grateful, they soiled the memories of his childhood.<P>            Nall sighed and slammed the tiller hard right as the continent of Odus came into view..<P>            -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Dirk punched the wall again and left a nasty dent in it roughly the size of a man’s head. He sat down slowly.<P>            “Why?” he whispered.<P>            Suddenly he was filled with a jet of new hatred for the man who had destroyed his life. It all came down to him, everything wrong<BR>            with life. He had no doubt he was even assisting with Trini’s kidnapping.<P>            He plunged into the book he always carried, ignoring the words, not paying attention so much to the passages as to the emotions<BR>            which rose in his heart. He cried for the first time in four years as he relived all the terrible experiences of his life. He was filled with a plague of loathing as he realized who’s fault it really, truly was. Everything, even Maxim.<P>It all came down to her and her kind.<P>            “Damn you, Veeshan. Cazic. All of you! ALL OF YOU! I HATE YOU! I HATE YOU ALL! Why can‘t you leave me alone?!!”<P>            Weeping, Dirk slammed his fist into the wall again, and watched the razor-sharp blades in his gauntlet emerge from the hidden, installed sheaths. There were three of them. A Reaper’s claws, taken from a dead adversary and fused with technology to create a potentially lethal and terrible weapon. They overlapped his fingers, obscuring them all so that only the blades could be seen from the top. He had rarely had to use them.<P>            Dirk smiled grimly and thought of revenge as he retracted the blades and steepled his fingers.<P>            -------------------------------------------<BR>(one Small bit left)
