<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Scott was dumped unceremoniously to the ground. His head swam and he battled nausea.<P>            “Didn’t expect us to come out here.” Eris’s voice. He clambered to his feet and saw her seemingly at ease, gazing into what he<BR>            recognized as a forest. The air was faintly obscured with a slightly yellowish mist.<P>            Toxxulia forest. He had trained here. His eyes slid over the terrain with a cool, appraising air. A jumbled collection of ancient stone<BR>            pillars was to his right. He was curious, because he felt a current of unbelievably strong mana flowing inside it. But it subsided even<BR>            as he acknowledged it.<P>            The hairs on his neck rose. Someone was nearby. He motioned silently to Eris and directed her behind one of the pillars, then crawled<BR>            behind one himself.<P>            “Funny. The mana surge seems to have disappeared. I wonder what could have caused that?” The voice was that of a soldier. Scott<BR>            cursed below his breath and drew his sword slowly, ever so slowly, and readied his submachine gun in his left hand. He could hear the<BR>            loading of Eris’s dual pistols. She preferred guns and katar, a kind of dangerous punching dagger.<P>            “I’ll check around here.” Another soldier. Scott appraised the situation. Most likely five. Patrols traveled in fives. He would have to<BR>            throw his own remaining grenade and open up with a lightning mana attack as soon as they got near.<P>            The rim of a helmet entered the corner of Scott’s eye. He threw away the pin and threw the grenade with an overhand toss, then<BR>            sprayed the area with a clip from his weapon.<P>            There was no explosion, just a shriek and a massive white flash. It was a whiteout grenade, and the cries of two men let him know it<BR>            had blinded them and shattered their sensors and radios with the concussion. He pointed his sword at one of them and yelled: “Arc<BR>            Strike!” A bolt of thunderous electricity leapt between them and the stench of burning plastics and flesh mixed. The scream of his<BR>            opponent was angry.<P>            He leapt out of the shelter of the pillars for a split second. He heard the roar of Eris’s pistols and saw red explode from the shoulders,<BR>            neck, and chest of one man, who tumbled like a puppet without a puppeteer.<BR>            Then a chip of stone cut him along the face as a bullet whizzed by his head.<P>            Imagine, if you will, the scene. Smoke mixing with the mist, the remaining four troopers advancing, and no sign of the assailants.<P>            Then it explodes once again. As two men came running his way and encircled him, Scott pulled his blade into the en garde position.<BR>            He twirled them out of the way, and with a series of spins and counters he protected himself from each while slowly bringing them<BR>            onto one side. To watch a skilled swordsman is a mesmerizing experience.<P>            Mesmerizing but deadly.<P>            Swords sang and almost before he knew what hit him, the first man was down, the blade of Scott’s weapon slicing though his armor<BR>            like paper and puncturing frail human flesh with a seemingly gentle stroke of it’s silken edge. He collapsed in a bloody mess, so<BR>            obviously dead that Scott spared him less then a nanosecond’s glance.<P>            The second man lasted only second longer as Scott raised the Despair with his hand. He was ambidextrous, and as the blade caught<BR>            the light it sucked it away, leaving shadow and he sprayed another clip of bullets at the man. He heard a grunt.. There was a low<BR>            shriek and the blade glowed black as it descended.<P>            The concussion as the Despair hit the enemy swordsman was devastating. Scott’s sight was hazy, but he saw the awful effect as the<BR>            sword literally separated his enemy from groin to crown with a single blow and turned the sword he was holding to steel shards. A<BR>            bloody mist hung in the air for a quarter of a second. The black trail the Despair left did not fade away, but slowly dissipated, leaving<BR>            the forest a little darker.<P>            Scott stood in a ready pose. The power of the dark blade flowed through his body like an intoxicating drug, fascinating him, dazzling<BR>            him. It made him feel invincible.<P>            Eris was doing well too. Bullets chattered around her as she whipped through the enemy ranks like a whirlwind, slicing with her katar.<BR>            The two men were bleeding from multiple wounds before they knew what hit them. Her normal aversion to combat had vanished.<P>            The two husks collapsed to the ground. Eris grinned halfheartedly at Scott.<P>            “Let’s move. Palsa.”<P>            The sound of rifles being readied stopped their grin. Scott’s head whipped around to reveal another ten men with weapons pointed.<P>            “Freeze.”<P>            Scott breathed slowly, then screamed. A bolt of lightning struck the enemy ranks-he had no idea how he had done it- and he yelled<BR>            “RUN ERIS!” as they started sprinting, dodging the bullets.<P>            The forest zipped by. He couldn’t see anything anymore of Eris, the soldiers, anyone alive-but for the bullets he could hear whining<BR>            past him.<P>            ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>            Preview of Next Chapter:<P>            As Maxim prepares to move upon Erollisi, the Naked Elf descends upon Odus with Dirk burning for revenge aboard. Nall muses upon his<BR>            mother’s death, and there is always the strange figure Rashan, which stalks them still through the dark skies.<P>            Scott and Eris are adrift in the forests and badlands of Odus, staying only one step away from capture and execution.<P>            What will happen? Find out in Chapter Five: Blood Moon<P>            --------------------<P>(That is a lot of text aint it? Well all done  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> Enjoy  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> )
